SECOND AMENDED AND RESTATED LARGE GENERATOR INTERCONNECTION AGREEMENT CO-TENANCY AGREEMENT This SECOND AMENDED AND RESTATED LARGE GENERATOR INTERCONNECTION AGREEMENT CO-TENANCY AGREEMENT (this “Agreement”) is made and entered into as of December 18, 2023, by and among Desert Sunlight 300, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Desert 300”), Desert Sunlight 250, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Desert 250”), Sunlight Storage, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Storage”), Sunlight Storage II, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Storage II”, and collectively with Desert 300, Desert 250, and Storage, the “Co-Tenants”), and Desert Sunlight Holdings, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (the “Manager”); each also a “Party” and collectively, the “Parties”. RECITALS A. Desert 300 has constructed, owns and operates a solar energy project with a net nameplate capacity of 300 MW in Desert Center, California. B. Desert 250 has constructed, owns and operates a solar energy project with a net nameplate capacity of 250 MW in Desert Center, California. C. Storage has constructed, owns and operates a battery storage facility with a net nameplate capacity of 230 MW co-located with the Desert 250 Facility, with which it shares its interconnection capacity. D. Storage II intends to construct, own and operate a battery storage facility with a projected net nameplate capacity of 230 MW to be co-located with the Desert 300 Facility and share its interconnection capacity. E. Desert 300 and Desert 250, as tenants-in-common, and Manager, as agent for Desert 300 and Desert 250, entered into that certain Assignment Agreement, dated as of July 21, 2011 (the “LGIA Assignment”), that certain First Amendment to the Standard Large Generator Interconnection Agreement by and among Manager, Desert 250, Desert 300, Southern California Edison Company (“SCE”) and the California Independent System Operator Corporation (the “CAISO”), dated as of August 19, 2011 (the “First LGIA Amendment”), that certain Second Amendment to the Standard Large Generator Interconnection Agreement, dated May 25, 2022 (the “Second LGIA Amendment”, which added Storage as an Interconnection Customer), that certain Third Amendment to the Standard Large Generator Interconnection Agreement, dated _________, 2023 (the “Third LGIA Amendment”, which added Storage II as an Interconnection Customer, and together with the First LGIA Amendment and the Second LGIA Amendment, the “LGIA Amendments”), in each case with respect to that certain Standard Large Generator Interconnection Agreement by and among Manager, SCE, and the CAISO, dated as of August 4, 2010 (all as amended by the LGIA Amendments and as may be further amended or supplemented, collectively, the “LGIA”) for the purpose of securing interconnection rights for each of the Facilities. F. In order to finance the Desert 250 Facility, Desert 250 entered into that certain Master Agreement, dated as of September 29, 2011 (as amended, restated, amended and restated, modified or supplemented from time to time, the “Desert 250 Master Agreement”), by and among Desert 250, the Manager, U.S. Department of Energy (“DOE”), the lenders and LC issuing banks party thereto from time to time, Deutsche Bank Trust Company Americas, as Master Administrative Agent, Collateral Agent, Intercreditor Agent, A-1 Administrative Agent, A-2 Administrative Agent, A-3 Administrative Agent and SPV Trustee, Citibank, N.A., as LC Facility Administrative Agent, and Goldman Sachs Lending Partners LLC and Citigroup Global Markets Inc., as Joint Syndication Agents, Joint Lead Arrangers and Joint Bookrunners. G. In order to finance the Desert 300 MW Generating Facility, Desert 300 entered into that certain Master Agreement, dated as of September 29, 2011 (as amended, restated, amended and restated, modified or supplemented from time to time, the “Desert 300 Master Agreement”, and together with the Desert 250 Master Agreement, the “Master Agreements”), by and among Desert 300, the Manager, DOE, the lenders and LC issuing banks party thereto from time to time, Deutsche Bank Trust Company Americas, as Master Administrative Agent, Collateral Agent, Intercreditor Agent, A-1 Administrative Agent, A-2 Administrative Agent, A-3 Administrative Agent and SPV Trustee, Citibank, N.A., as LC Facility Administrative Agent, and Goldman Sachs Lending Partners LLC and Citigroup Global Markets Inc., as Joint Syndication Agents, Joint Lead Arrangers and Joint Bookrunners. H. The Parties amended and restated the Large Generator Interconnection Agreement Co-Tenancy Agreement, dated as of August 19, 2011, and the first amendment to the Large Generator Interconnection Co-Tenancy Agreement, dated as of September 28, 2011 (collectively, the “Original Agreement”), with that certain Amended and Restated Large Generator Interconnection Agreement Co-Tenancy Agreement dated as of May 25, 2022 (the “A&R Agreement”), between the Parties to those agreements, to set forth the rights and obligations of each of the Parties under the LGIA. I. The Parties desire to enter into this Agreement, which replaces the Original Agreement (as amended and restated by the A&R Agreement). ARTICLE II CO-TENANCY RIGHTS AND OBLIGATIONS 2.1 Use of LGIA . The LGIA shall be held and used solely to permit the interconnection of electricity generated (in the case of Desert 250 and Desert 300), or charged and discharged (in the case of Storage and Storage II), by or on behalf of a Co-Tenant (or by such Co-Tenant’s successors or assigns) at the Red Bluff Substation. Desert 300 and Desert 250 have an undivided ownership interest as tenants-in-common in the Interconnection Facilities, and each Co-Tenant shares in the rights and obligations of the Interconnection Customer and the LGIA equal to its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest, and possesses an undivided right to enjoy all of such interest in the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA. Each of Storage and Storage II is a party to the LGIA as an Interconnection Customer, and Desert 250 and Storage will share the Desert 250 interests (“Desert 250/Storage Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest”) as provided herein and Desert 300 and Storage II will share the Desert 300 interests (“Desert 300/Storage II Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest”). 2.2 Maximum Capacity . Desert 300 and Storage II, collectively, shall not interconnect and operate their Facilities to the Red Bluff Substation to the extent such operations will result in Desert 300 having (a) a Maximum Net Nameplate Capacity in excess of (b) the product of (i) Desert 300/Storage II’s Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest and (ii) 550 MW. Desert 250 and Storage, collectively, shall not interconnect and operate their Facilities to the Red Bluff Substation to the extent such operations would result in such Desert 250 and Storage collectively having (a) a Maximum Net Nameplate Capacity in excess of (b) the product of (i) Desert 250/Storage’s Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest and (ii) 550 MW. To the extent that conditions exist which result in, collectively, Desert 250 combined with Storage generating or discharging energy in excess of the Desert 250/Storage Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest, Desert 250 and/or Storage, as applicable, shall curtail the operation of its respective Facility so as not to exceed the Desert 250/Storage Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest of the interconnection capacity. To the extent that conditions exist which result in, collectively, Desert 300 combined with Storage II generating in excess of the Desert 300/Storage II Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest, then Desert 300 and/or Storage II, as applicable, shall curtail the operation of its respective Facility so as not to exceed the Desert 300/Storage II Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest of the interconnection capacity. 2.3 Priority of Use of Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest . (a) Unless subject to requirements of the CAISO tariff, Desert 250 Facility shall at all times be entitled to the full Desert 250/Storage Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest to deliver all of the Desert 250 Facility’s energy to the Point of Interconnection as defined in the LGIA. Only to the extent that Desert 250 is not fully utilizing the Desert 250/Storage Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest, the Storage Facility shall be entitled to utilize the Desert 250/Storage Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest to deliver up to 230 MW of energy from the Storage Facility to the Point of Interconnection. (b) Unless subject to requirements of the CAISO tariff, Desert 300 Facility shall at all times be entitled to the full Desert 300/Storage II Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest to deliver all of the Desert 300 Facility’s energy to the Point of Interconnection as defined in the LGIA. Only to the extent that Desert 300 is not fully utilizing the Desert 300/Storage II Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest, the Storage II Facility shall be entitled to utilize the Desert 300/Storage II Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest to deliver up to 230 MW of energy from the Storage II Facility to the Point of Interconnection. 2.4 Curtailment. In the event of any curtailment of interconnection services at the direction of CAISO or Participating TO, such curtailment shall be allocated pro rata among the Desert 300/Storage II Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest and Desert 250/Storage Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest; provided, however, unless required otherwise pursuant to, or to comply with, the LGIA or the CAISO tariff, with respect to (a) the Desert 250/Storage Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest, the Manager shall curtail the energy from the Storage Facility to the Point of Interconnection before it curtails energy from the Desert 250 Facility and (b) the Desert 300/Storage II Co-Tenancy Percentage, the Manager shall curtail the energy from the Storage II Facility to the Point of Interconnection before it curtails energy from the Desert 300 Facility, and provided that the Manager shall only curtail Desert 300/Storage II Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest and Desert 250/Storage Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest on a non-pro rata basis if, with respect to any curtailment of an amount less than 5 megawatts and for a limited duration not to exceed 6 hours, it reasonably determines that non-pro rata allocation of such curtailment is necessary to comply with the LGIA or CAISO or Participating TO direction, and, in each case, that such non-pro rata allocation will not result in a default under the LGIA. 2.5 LGIA Expenses . Each Co-Tenant hereby confirms its obligation to share in the periodic payment of all expenses incurred under the LGIA in accordance with its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest, as modified below: 1) Construction Costs. Storage agrees to fund all Construction Costs required to design, engineer and construct the Participating TO’s Interconnection Facilities and Interconnection Customer’s Interconnection Facilities pursuant to the LGIA for the interconnection of the Storage Facility, and agrees to design, engineer and construct Storage Facility’s Interconnection Facilities. Storage II agrees to fund all Construction Costs required to design, engineer and construct the Participating TO’s Interconnection Facilities and Interconnection Customer’s Interconnection Facilities pursuant to the LGIA for the interconnection of the Storage II Facility, and agrees to design, engineer and construct Storage II Facility’s Interconnection Facilities. 2) LGIA Operating Expenses. Desert 300 and Storage II collectively shall be responsible for the payment of their pro rata share of the LGIA Operating Expenses in accordance with the Desert 300/Storage II Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest, and Desert 250 and Storage collectively shall be responsible for the payment of their pro rata share of the LGIA Operating Expenses in accordance with the Desert 250/Storage Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest. With respect to Desert 250 and Storage, Desert 250 and Storage shall each be responsible for payment of fifty percent (50%) of the operating expenses allocated to the Desert 250/Storage Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest. With respect to Desert 300 and Storage II, Desert 300 and Storage II shall each be responsible for payment of fifty percent (50%) of the operating expenses allocated to the Desert 300/Storage II Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest. 3) Payment of LGIA Expenses. The Manager shall, as authorized agent for each Co-Tenant, administer the collection and payment of the LGIA Operating Expenses and other amounts due from the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA. Each Co-Tenant obligated to pay LGIA Operating Expenses and other amounts under the LGIA shall pay each invoice for LGIA costs promptly upon receipt of written notice thereof from the Manager, but in any event within thirty (30) days of such receipt or such earlier time as required by the LGIA. 2.6 Liquidated Damages; Credits; Refunds . To the extent that the Manager receives any damages, credits or refunds pursuant to the LGIA, the Manager shall promptly remit such damages, credits or refunds to the Co-Tenants according to each Co-Tenant’s Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest (unless such damages, credits or refunds accrue to a specific Co-Tenant, in which event the Manager shall promptly remit them to such Co-Tenant). With respect to (i) Desert 250 and Storage, damages, credits or refunds associated with such Desert 250/Storage Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest shall be allocated on a 50/50 basis to Desert 250 and Storage and (ii) Desert 300 and Storage II, damages, credits or refunds associated with such Desert 300/Storage II Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest shall be allocated on a 50/50 basis to Desert 300 and Storage II. 2.7 Joint and Several Liability . Each Co-Tenant shall be jointly and severally liable for (i) any payments due under the LGIA imposed on the Interconnection Customer and (ii) the performance of the obligations and duties imposed on the Interconnection Customer by the LGIA; provided, however, that each Party shall be severally, and not, jointly liable for all other obligations hereunder. In the event Storage or Storage II fails to make its share of payments due under LGIA, and Desert 300 or Desert 250 makes such payment on behalf of Storage or Storage II, Storage or Storage II, as applicable, will reimburse the Co-Tenant that makes such payment within thirty (30) days. 2.8 Projected Storage and Storage II Facility Capacity . The projected Maximum Net Nameplate Capacity of each of the Storage Facility and the Storage II Facility is reflected in Exhibit A, as may be amended, but subject in all respects to Section 2.2. 2.9 Indemnity . 1) Each Co-Tenant (an “Indemnifying Co-Tenant”) shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Co-Tenants (each, an “Indemnified Co-Tenant”) from and against any and all losses (including all lost revenues under applicable PPAs), damages, liabilities, claims, judgments, liens, penalties, costs and expenses, including, without limitation, reasonable attorneys’ and consultants’ fees (collectively, “Claims”), which may be imposed upon or incurred by such Indemnified Co-Tenant or asserted against such Indemnified Co-Tenant in connection with any breach by the Indemnifying Co-Tenant of this Agreement or the LGIA. 2) The Manager shall indemnify, defend, and hold harmless the Co-Tenants from any Claims which may be imposed upon or incurred by such Co-Tenants as a result of fraud, willful misconduct, or gross negligence of the Manager. 2.10 Taxes . Each Co-Tenant shall pay all real and personal property taxes and assessments, general or special, levied against its Facility except for any taxes or assessments that are LGIA Operating Expenses. All such taxes and assessments shall be paid before delinquency and before any fine, interest or penalty shall become due or be imposed for their non-payment; provided if a Co-Tenant in good faith contests or disputes such taxes or assessments and furnishes to the other Co-Tenants a bond or other acceptable security in an amount sufficient to discharge all such contested taxes or assessments, such Co-Tenant will not be in default under this Section 2.11 for failing to timely pay such contested taxes or assessments. 2.11 Operation and Management . 1) Each Co-Tenant shall operate and maintain its Facility Controlled Assets acting as a prudent operator and manager and otherwise (a) in accordance with the terms of the LGIA, (b) in accordance with good operating and utility industry practices, (c) in compliance with all applicable Laws, including but not limited to the Federal Power Act, as amended (“FPA”), and all rules, regulations, and orders issued by the FERC pursuant to the FPA, (d) in compliance with the CAISO Tariff, including the rules, protocols, procedures and standards attached thereto, as the same may be amended from time to time and approved by FERC, (e) in compliance with the rules, protocols, procedures and standards of NERC, and (f) without causing a material adverse effect on the LGIA. 2) Each Co-Tenant shall comply with its obligations under the LGIA, including with respect to its obligations to fund LGIA Operating Expenses. Each Co-Tenant shall obtain and maintain status as an “exempt wholesale generator” or a “qualifying facility” under applicable Law. 3) Each Co-Tenant shall cooperate with and timely respond to Manager as agent for the Co-Tenants under the LGIA, and shall provide Manager such information required by Manager to comply with its obligations under the LGIA. 4) With respect to jointly held assets, the Co-Tenants may delegate to the Manager some or all of their respective obligations under this Agreement. 2.12 Events of Default: Default . The following shall constitute “Events of Default”: a Party fails to perform its obligations under this Agreement or the LGIA in any material respect, and such Party fails to cure such default within (i) ten (10) days after receipt of written notice of a payment default, or (ii) twenty (20) days after receipt of written notice of any non-payment default, provided if the nature of the defaulted obligation or obligations other than a payment default is such that more than thirty (30) days are required, in the exercise of commercially reasonable diligence, for cure of such default, then such Co-Tenant shall not be in default under this Section 2.13 if it commences to cure such default within twenty (20) days after receiving notice of the default and thereafter continuously pursues the same to completion with commercially reasonable diligence, such extended period not to exceed sixty (60) days, including the initial cure period. 2.13 Remedies . Subject to the last sentence of Section 5.8, in addition to all other remedies permitted by Law or under this Agreement (all of which shall be cumulative), following an Event of Default, each non-defaulting Party shall have the right, but not the obligation, to perform the obligations of the defaulting Party, and the defaulting Party shall reimburse the performing Parties for their expenses which they incurred in rendering the performance, plus interest at the Interest Rate. 2.14 Disconnection . 1) If a Co-Tenant fails to cure any default of it under this Agreement or the LGIA within twenty five (25) days after receiving notice of such default, the Manager may disconnect the breaching Co-Tenant’s Facility from the Red Bluff Substation (i) after obtaining written approval to do so from the Co-Tenant then not in default, or (ii) without approval from the Co-Tenant but only to the extent necessary to prevent or cure a “Default” under the LGIA; provided if the nature of the defaulted obligation or obligations is such that more than thirty (30) days are required, in the exercise of commercially reasonable diligence, for cure of such default, then the Manager may not disconnect the defaulting Co-Tenant’s Facility if such Co-Tenant commences to cure such default within twenty five (25) days after receiving notice of the default and thereafter continuously pursues the same to completion with commercially reasonable diligence, such extended period not to exceed eighty five (85) days, including the initial cure period; provided further, that in no event shall any cure period hereunder extend beyond any applicable cure period under the LGIA. 2) To the extent caused by a Co-Tenant’s default hereunder, the Manager may also disconnect such Co-Tenant’s Facility in order to prevent damage to another Co-Tenant’s Facility, the Interconnection Facilities or the property of SCE or as otherwise needed to prevent or mitigate technical issues affecting the Facilities; the Manager shall immediately notify the Co-Tenants of any such disconnection. 2.15 Equitable Relief . The Parties agree that damages may be an inadequate remedy for a breach by the Manager or any other Party of its respective obligations under this Agreement, and that each Party shall be entitled to seek injunctive and other equitable relief, including specific performance, against any other Party or the Manager to prevent or eliminate such default. 2.16 Dispute Resolution . 1) Submission. In the event any Party has a dispute, or asserts a claim, that arises out of or in connection with this Agreement or the LGIA, such Party (the “Disputing Party”) shall provide the other Parties with written notice of the dispute or claim (“Notice of Dispute”). Such dispute or claim shall be referred to a designated senior representative of each Party for resolution on an informal basis as promptly as practicable after receipt of the Notice of Dispute by the Parties. In the event the designated representatives are unable to resolve the claim or dispute through unassisted or assisted negotiations within thirty (30) days of the other Parties’ receipt of the Notice of Dispute, such claim or dispute may, upon mutual agreement of the Parties, be submitted to arbitration and resolved in accordance with the arbitration procedures set forth below. In the event the Parties do not agree within such thirty (30) day period to submit such claim or dispute to arbitration, each Party may exercise whatever rights and remedies it may have in equity or at law consistent with the terms of this Agreement. 2) Arbitration Procedures. Any arbitration initiated under this Agreement shall be conducted before a single neutral arbitrator appointed by the Parties. The arbitrator shall be knowledgeable in electric utility matters, including electric transmission and bulk power issues, and shall not have any current or past substantial business or financial relationships with any party to the arbitration (except prior arbitration). The arbitrator shall provide each of the Parties an opportunity to be heard and, except as otherwise provided herein, shall conduct the arbitration in accordance with the Commercial Arbitration Rules of the American Arbitration Association (“Arbitration Rules”) and any applicable FERC regulations; provided, however, in the event of a conflict between the Arbitration Rules and the terms of this Section 2.17, the terms of this Section 2.17 shall prevail. 3) Arbitration Decisions. Unless otherwise agreed by the Parties, the arbitrator shall render a decision within ninety (90) days of appointment and shall notify the Parties in writing of such decision and the reasons therefor. The arbitrator shall be authorized only to interpret and apply the provisions of this Agreement and the LGIA and shall have no power to modify or change any provision of such agreements in any manner. The decision of the arbitrator shall be final and binding upon the Parties, and judgment on the award may be entered in any court having jurisdiction. The decision of the arbitrator may be appealed solely on the grounds that the conduct of the arbitrator, or the decision itself, violated the standards set forth in the Federal Arbitration Act or the Administrative Dispute Resolution Act. The final decision of the arbitrator must also be filed with FERC if it affects jurisdictional rates, terms and conditions of service, Interconnection Facilities, or Network Upgrades. 4) Costs. Each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for its own costs incurred during the arbitration process and for such Co-Tenant’s Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest of the cost of the arbitrator chosen, if applicable. 2.17 Effect of Force Majeure . If, because of an event of Force Majeure, any Party is unable to carry out its obligations under this Agreement, and if such Party promptly gives the other Parties written notice of such Force Majeure in detail, specifying the nature, extent and expected duration of such Force Majeure, the non-payment obligations and liabilities of the Party giving such notice and the corresponding obligations and liabilities of any other Party shall be temporarily suspended to the extent made necessary by and during the continuance of such Force Majeure; provided, that in no event will the suspension of a Party’s obligations and liabilities hereunder be permitted to cause a “Default” under the LGIA. Any disabling effects of such event of Force Majeure shall be eliminated as soon as and to the extent reasonably practicable by the Party claiming Force Majeure. 2.18 Notice of Default . Each Co-Tenant and the Manager shall promptly provide written notice to the other Parties upon receiving notice of, or otherwise discovering, any default or potential default under this Agreement or the LGIA or receiving any other notice under the LGIA. ARTICLE III MANAGER 3.1 Appointment of Manager: Manager Services . Each Co-Tenant hereby appoints the Manager to act as its agent and representative for all purposes under the LGIA and coordinate compliance with the LGIA by the Co-Tenants, unless otherwise agreed by the Co-Tenants. For the avoidance of doubt, any amendment, waiver, modification, termination or Transfer of the LGIA shall be made only in accordance with the terms of the LGIA. In addition, Desert 250 and Desert 300 each specifically authorizes the Manager to negotiate and, with Desert 250 or Desert 300’s prior written consent, as applicable, execute on its behalf and on behalf of the Interconnection Customer, and agrees to be bound by the terms of, (i) a CAISO meter service agreement, (ii) a CAISO participating generator agreement and (iii) a SCE retail electricity service agreement; provided that, to the extent that the Manager acts as agent for Desert 250 or Desert 300 under any such agreement, the Manager may not terminate, amend or Transfer any such agreement or waive any material rights of Desert 250 or Desert 300 under any such agreement or initiate or settle any dispute resolution under any such agreement, without the prior written consent of Desert 250 or Desert 300, as applicable. 3.2 Communications . The Manager shall be the single point of contact between the Co-Tenants and the CAISO and SCE, and shall be responsible for all administrative obligations of the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA, including billing, issuing payments, providing notices and communicating with, and receiving instructions from, the CAISO and SCE with respect to the Facilities and the LGIA. The Manager shall, promptly upon receipt, provide to each Co-Tenant a copy of any notices or other material communications received by it under the LGIA. 3.3 Indemnification of Manager . Each Co-Tenant shall, pro rata in accordance with its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest, defend, indemnify and hold harmless the Manager and its employees and agents, from any claim, loss, liability or damage incurred by reason of any act performed or omitted to be performed by it in its reasonable judgment, in good faith, or in reasonable reliance on advice of the Manager’s attorneys or accountants, in connection with the LGIA or this Agreement (other than acts or omissions constituting a material breach by the Manager of this Agreement or the fraud, willful misconduct, or gross negligence of the Manager), including reasonable attorneys’ fees incurred by it in connection with the defense of any action based on any such alleged act or omission. The Manager shall specifically be indemnified by the Co-Tenants pro rata in accordance with their Co-Tenancy Percentage Interests (provided that (i) with respect to Desert 250 and Storage, Desert 250 and Storage shall each be responsible for payment of fifty percent (50%) of the operating expenses allocated to the Desert 250/Storage Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest and (ii) with respect to Desert 300 and Storage II, Desert 300 and Storage II shall each be responsible for payment of fifty percent (50%) of the operating expenses allocated to the Desert 300/Storage II Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest) and held harmless from any and all actions taken by the Manager in its reasonable judgment, in good faith, or in reasonable reliance on advice of the Manager's attorneys or accountants, and shall be reimbursed by the Co-Tenants pro rata in accordance with their Co-Tenancy Percentage Interests (provided that (i) with respect to Desert 250 and Storage, Desert 250 and Storage shall each be responsible for payment of fifty percent (50%) of the operating expenses allocated to the Desert 250/Storage Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest and (ii) with respect to Desert 300 and Storage II, Desert 300 and Storage II shall each be responsible for payment of fifty percent (50%) of the operating expenses allocated to the Desert 300/Storage II Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest) for costs, which arise in connection with the LGIA or this Agreement (other than costs resulting from a material breach by the Manager of this Agreement or the fraud, willful misconduct, or gross negligence of the Manager) . 3.4 Books and Records; Reporting Requirements . 1) Maintenance or Records. The Manager shall maintain books and records in sufficient detail to verify amounts due and payable hereunder for a period of not less than three (3) years after the end of the calendar month to which they relate, and all such books and records shall be available for inspection and/or copying by each Co-Tenant or its authorized representative at the cost and expense of such Co-Tenant and at reasonable times during regular business hours, upon reasonable notice to the Manager. 2) Provision of Records. The Manager shall, from time to time or at the reasonable request of the Co-Tenants or their Financing Parties, provide reports to the Co-Tenants and their Financing Parties sufficient to keep the Co-Tenants and their Financing Parties reasonably apprised as to significant matters concerning the LGIA, the Construction Costs and the LGIA Operating Costs. 3.5 Replacement of Manager . Upon the written approval of the Co-Tenants, the Co-Tenants may replace the Manager with any Person of their choosing; provided, however, that any Co-Tenant (acting by itself) may remove the Manager (a) in the event of bankruptcy or liquidation, either voluntary or involuntary, of the Manager, the winding-up of Manager or seizure on any of the assets of Manager, or the taking of any action by any person for the purpose of effecting any of the foregoing (“Manager Insolvency”), or (b) if the Manager is in material default hereunder. If a Co-Tenant (acting by itself) removes the Manager as a result of Manager Insolvency or a material default by Manager hereunder, the Co-Tenants shall jointly appoint a new Manager and provide written notice to CAISO and Participating TO of the new Manager. 3.6 Management Fee . In consideration of the services provided by Manager hereunder, the Manager shall be paid an annual fee of One Thousand Five Hundred Dollars ($1,500.00) (the “Management Fee”), payable monthly, in advance, in equal monthly installments, beginning on the date hereof and ending on the termination of this Agreement or the replacement of the Manager. The Management Fee shall be allocated to the Co-Tenants as an LGIA Operating Expense. 3.7 Discrimination . Notwithstanding any other provision herein to the contrary (other than Sections 2.4, 2.5 and 2.15), the Manager shall not Discriminate in providing services or otherwise performing its obligations hereunder among the Co-Tenants. As used herein, “Discriminate” means a failure by the Manager to provide services hereunder in a manner that treats alike each of the Co-Tenants under substantially similar conditions, and for which dissimilar treatment is not otherwise justified as necessary in accordance with prudent operating and utility industry practices. 3.8 Performance . The Manager shall perform its obligations under this Agreement (a) in accordance with the terms of the LGIA, (b) in accordance with good operating and utility industry practices, (c) in compliance with all applicable Laws, including but not limited to the FPA, and all rules, regulations, and orders issued by the FERC pursuant to the FPA, (d) in compliance with the CAISO Tariff, including the rules, protocols, procedures and standards attached thereto, as the same may be amended from time to time and approved by FERC, (e) incompliance with the rules, protocols, procedures and standards of NERC, and (f) without causing a material adverse effect on the LGIA. ARTICLE IV TRANSFERABILITY 4.1 General Restriction . Manager shall not Transfer its rights and obligations under this Agreement. No Co-Tenant may Transfer its rights and obligations under this Agreement or the LGIA; provided, however, that each Co-Tenant shall Transfer (such Transfer not requiring the consent of a Party) its rights and obligations under this Agreement and the LGIA to a transferee of its respective Facility Controlled Assets (in which case such transferee shall be assigned and assume all of the Transferring Co-Tenant’s rights and obligations under both this Agreement and the LGIA, pursuant to an agreement reasonably satisfactory to the other Co-Tenants). 4.2 Co-Tenant’s Right to Encumber . Should a Co-Tenant incur any encumbrance in accordance with Section 4.2 of this Agreement, and should the Parties receive notice thereof pursuant to Section 5.1 hereof, the Parties hereby expressly stipulate and agree as follows: 1) Modification of Agreement. Each Party shall provide any information reasonably requested by any other Party in connection with any filing made pursuant to Section 3.1 and shall otherwise reasonably cooperate with, and act in good faith to assist, the Parties in acquiring any necessary or desirable FERC action with respect to this Agreement. 3) Notwithstanding anything in Section 4.1 or 4.2 to the contrary, no Transfer of a Co-Tenant’s interests in this Agreement shall be effective unless and until the Co-Tenant or the Manager has obtained any necessary prior approvals from the FERC to effectuate any changes to this Agreement to reflect such Transfer and the change in the parties to this Agreement. SHARED FACILITIES AND RIGHTS AND THE GENERATING FACILITIES 4.1 Shared Facilities and Rights. 4.1.1 Ownership. (a) The Co-Tenants shall own the Shared Facilities and Rights as tenants-in-common, with each Co-Tenant owning an undivided ownership interest in all Shared Facilities and Rights in proportion to its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest (a “Co-Tenancy Interest”). The Co-Tenants acknowledge and agree that, with respect to the Shared Facilities and Rights in or to which the Manager or either or both of the Co-Tenants acquired an interest or right before or on the Effective Date other than the Unassigned Shared Facilities and Rights, each Co-Tenant owns its Co-Tenancy Interest therein. Each Co-Tenant shall comply with all the terms and conditions of the Shared Facilities and Rights Agreements and Governmental Approvals for the Shared Facilities and Rights. Unless otherwise determined by the Co-Tenants, any Co-Tenant that holds in its own name, or an Affiliate’s name, any Unassigned Shared Facilities and Rights shall hold the same subject in all respects to this Agreement, and such Co-Tenant shall transfer and assign an undivided ownership interest therein to the other Co-Tenant equal to such other Co-Tenant’s Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest as soon as practicable after the Effective Date, and do all things necessary or appropriate to register or record on any appropriate register the asset in the names of the Co-Tenants; provided, however, that the foregoing shall not restrict any Co-Tenant from partitioning those portions of any Unassigned Shared Facilities and Rights that are solely for the benefit of a Generating Facility, it being understood and agreed by the Co-Tenants that, in such event, a Co-Tenant’s obligations hereunder with respect to any such Unassigned Shared Facilities and Rights shall not apply to the portions so partitioned and the portions so partitioned shall not constitute Shared Facilities and Rights, notwithstanding anything in this Agreement to the contrary. If any of the Unassigned Shared Facilities and Rights is encumbered by Liens (other than Excluded Liens) at the time of such conveyance, such Co-Tenant shall promptly and diligently work to remove such Liens therefrom. (b) The Co-Tenants each hereby grant to Sunlight Storage and Sunlight Storage II during the Term, and on the terms and subject to the conditions hereof, the non-exclusive right to access and utilize the Shared Facilities and Rights as may be necessary in connection with the development, construction, operation, maintenance and ownership of the Sunlight Storage Generating Facility and the Sunlight Storage II Generating Facility, as applicable, in a manner consistent with the LGIA Co-Tenancy Agreement. Each Party hereby acknowledges that the right of Sunlight Storage and Sunlight Storage II to access and utilize the Shared Facilities is essential to the operation and maintenance of the Sunlight Storage Generating Facility and the Sunlight Storage II Generating Facility, respectively. In exchange for such access and usage rights, (1) Sunlight Storage agrees to pay to the Co-Tenants during the Term an embedded cost rate based on Desert 250’s share of such costs that is discounted to reflect the non-firm access and usage rights hereunder, which rate shall be $276,000/year, subject to acceptance by FERC and (2) Sunlight Storage II agrees to pay to the Co-Tenants during the Term an embedded cost rate based on Desert 300’s share of such costs that is discounted to reflect the non-firm access and usage rights hereunder, which rate shall be $284,000/year, subject to acceptance by FERC. The Co-Tenants agree that such rate shall be shared between the Co-Tenants in accordance with their Co-Tenancy Percentage Interests. Notwithstanding the foregoing, upon the occurrence and during the continuation of an “Event of Default” (as defined in the Master Agreements), such rate shall increase to $750,000/year pro rated for such time as such “Event of Default” is continuing; provided, however, that if any such “Event of Default” is no longer continuing due to the disposition of the entirety of the Shared Facilities and Rights or the sale of the direct or indirect equity interests in any Co-Tenant, the $750,000 fee shall stay in effect permanently. Each of Sunlight Storage and Sunlight Storage II has received, has reviewed and agrees not to violate any term or condition of the Shared Facilities and Rights Agreements and Governmental Approvals for the Shared Facilities and Rights. (c) Notwithstanding the foregoing or anything else in this Agreement to the contrary, the Parties acknowledge and agree that the Manager, in addition to the Project Companies, may be a party to one or more of the Shared Facilities and Rights Agreements and/or the Governmental Approvals for the Shared Facilities and Rights. Without limiting the generality of Section 4.3, the Manager shall comply with all the terms and conditions of such Shared Facilities and Rights Agreements and Governmental Approvals. 4.1.2 Waiver of Partition . The Co-Tenants recognize that the physical partition of the Shared Facilities and Rights or any part thereof, whether by partition in-kind or sale and division of the proceeds thereof, would be impossible and impractical and wholly inconsistent with the purposes for which this Agreement is made. ACCORDINGLY, EACH CO-TENANT HEREBY AGREES (FOR ITSELF AND FOR EACH OF ITS SUCCESSORS AND ASSIGNS) THAT IT SHALL NOT TAKE ANY ACTION AT ANY TIME, BY JUDICIAL PROCEEDING OR OTHERWISE, TO PARTITION THE SHARED FACILITIES AND RIGHTS OR ANY PART THEREOF, IN ANY WAY, WHETHER BY PARTITION IN KIND OR BY SALE AND DIVISION OF THE PROCEEDS THEREOF. FURTHER, EACH CO-TENANT IRREVOCABLY WAIVES THE RIGHT OF PARTITION AND THE BENEFIT OF ALL STATUTORY OR COMMON LAW THAT MAY NOW OR HEREAFTER AUTHORIZE SUCH PARTITION OF THE SHARED FACILITIES AND RIGHTS OR ANY PART THEREOF. THE CO-TENANTS AGREE THAT THIS SECTION 4.1.2 SHALL BE INCLUDED VERBATIM IN THE MEMORANDUM TO BE RECORDED PURSUANT TO SECTION 10.16(b). 4.1.3 Use. (a) Each Project Company may use the Shared Facilities and Rights for the purpose of transmitting energy from, and receiving energy for, its Generating Facility in accordance with the LGIA Co-Tenancy Agreement. Each Project Company shall only interconnect its Generating Facility (and no other facility) to the Shared Facilities. Except as otherwise agreed to by the Project Companies, all Shared Facilities and Rights Agreements and Governmental Approvals for the Shared Facilities and Rights shall be in the name of both Co-Tenants. (b) In no event shall any Project Company’s use of the Shared Facilities and Rights or operation of its Generating Facility interfere with the use and quiet enjoyment by any Co-Tenant of such other Co-Tenant’s Co-Tenancy Interests in, or any Project Company’s rights to use, the Shared Facilities and Rights or any other Project Company’s operation of its Generating Facility, except as specifically provided herein or as agreed to by the Project Companies. Each of the Project Companies shall cooperate in good faith to accommodate the other Project Companies’ use of the Shared Facilities and Rights for the benefit of each other Project Company’s Generating Facility, as contemplated by this Agreement. The Project Companies acknowledge and agree that the use of the Shared Facilities and Rights by any Project Company in connection with its Generating Facility, as contemplated herein, will not, separately or in the aggregate, constitute an overburdening of the Shared Facilities and Rights or any part thereof. No Project Company shall use or permit the use of the Shared Facilities and Rights in any manner that would create unreasonable waste or nuisance, or that would jeopardize the issuance or maintenance of any insurance policy relating to the Shared Facilities and Rights or any Governmental Approval for the Shared Facilities and Rights or any Generating Facility, or otherwise conduct or cause to be conducted operations with respect to the Shared Facilities or such Project Company’s Generating Facility that would have a similar effect on, or otherwise materially damage or interfere with, the Shared Facilities and Rights, unless otherwise agreed to by the Project Companies. 4.1.4 Revenue and Energy . Any energy, and revenue attributable to the energy, produced or transmitted by a Generating Facility shall be only for the benefit of the Project Company owning such Generating Facility based on the amount of energy transmitted into the Shared Facilities from such Project Company’s Generating Facility, as adjusted for line losses on the Shared Facilities in accordance with this Agreement. 4.1.5 After-Acquired Property and Rights . Unless otherwise determined by the Co-Tenants, any Co-Tenant that acquires in its own name, or an Affiliate’s name, any After-Acquired Shared Facilities and Rights shall acquire and hold the same subject in all respects to this Agreement, and such Co-Tenant shall transfer and assign an undivided ownership interest therein to the other Co-Tenant equal to such other Co-Tenant’s Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest within fifteen (15) days after such acquisition, and do all things necessary or appropriate to register or record on any appropriate register the asset in the names of the Co-Tenants. In no event shall Sunlight Storage or Sunlight Storage II own any After-Acquired Shared Facilities and Rights. 4.2 Joint Responsibilities of the Project Companies . For purposes of this Agreement and the LGIA Co-Tenancy Agreement, an “Event of Default” under the LGIA Co-Tenancy Agreement shall be an Event of Default hereunder and an Event of Default hereunder shall be an “Event of Default” under the LGIA Co-Tenancy Agreement, and, for purposes of Section 9.2.3, a payment default that has resulted in an “Event of Default” under the LGIA Co-Tenancy Agreement shall be an Event of Default under Section 9.1.1. 9.2 Remedies. 9.2.1 Cumulative Remedies . Subject to Section 2.1, if an Event of Default occurs, each Non-Defaulting Party shall be entitled to all legal and equitable remedies at law or in equity not expressly prohibited by the terms of this Agreement. 9.2.2 Specific Performance . Each Party acknowledges and agrees that the failure to perform any of its obligations under this Agreement would cause irreparable harm to the other Parties and that the remedy at law for any violation or threatened violation thereof would be inadequate, and further agrees that the other Parties shall be entitled to a temporary or permanent injunction, specific performance or other equitable relief specifically to enforce such obligations without the necessity of proving the inadequacy of its legal remedies. No Party shall be required to post any guaranty, letter of credit, bond or other security to obtain an order or decree of temporary or permanent injunction, specific performance or other equitable relief. 9.2.3 Loss of Right to Shared Facilities and Rights . If an Event of Default occurs under Section 9.1.1, then, without limiting any other rights that any Non-Defaulting Party might otherwise have, upon notice to the Defaulting Party delivered while such Event of Default remains outstanding, (a) any Non-Defaulting Party may curtail such Defaulting Party’s benefit or use of, or access to, the Shared Facilities and Rights and (b) if a Project Company is a Non-Defaulting Party, such Project Company may receive all or any part of the Defaulting Party’s rights under this Agreement to benefit, use and access the Shared Facilities and Rights (or, if not practicable due to regulatory requirements or the rights of third Persons, the Defaulting Party shall promptly pay over to such Project Company all proceeds from its benefit, use and access of the Shared Facilities and Rights) until such time as such Non-Defaulting Party has received an amount equal to the payment default plus interest at the Interest Rate. 9.2.4 Cure Rights . If an Event of Default has occurred that could reasonably be expected to have a material adverse effect on the Shared Facilities and Rights or under Section 9.1.5, then, without limiting any other rights that the Non-Defaulting Party might have, upon notice to the Defaulting Party delivered while such Event of Default remains outstanding, each Non-Defaulting Party may cure such Event of Default at the Defaulting Party’s expense; provided, however, that no Party shall have the right to make any modification to any Generating Facility that is not owned by such Party. 10. GENERAL 10.1 Disputes. 10.1.1 Notice; Referral . In the event any Party has a dispute, or asserts a claim, that arises out of or in connection with this Agreement, such Party (the “Disputing Party”) shall provide the other Parties with written notice of the dispute or claim (“Notice of Dispute”). Such dispute or claim shall be referred to a designated senior representative of each Party for resolution on an informal basis as promptly as practicable after receipt of the Notice of Dispute by the Parties. In the event the designated representatives are unable to resolve the claim or dispute through unassisted or assisted negotiations within thirty (30) days of the other Parties’ receipt of the Notice of Dispute, such claim or dispute may, upon mutual agreement of the Parties, be submitted to arbitration and resolved in accordance with the arbitration procedures set forth below. In the event the Parties do not agree within such thirty (30)-day period to submit such claim or dispute to arbitration, each Party may exercise whatever rights and remedies it may have in equity or at law consistent with the terms of this Agreement. 10.1.2 Arbitration Rules . Any arbitration initiated under this Agreement shall be conducted before a single neutral arbitrator appointed by the Parties. The arbitrator shall be knowledgeable in electric utility matters, including electric transmission and bulk power issues, and shall not have any current or past substantial business or financial relationships with any party to the arbitration (except prior arbitration). The arbitrator shall provide each of the Parties an opportunity to be heard and, except as otherwise provided herein, shall conduct the arbitration in accordance with the Commercial Arbitration Rules of the American Arbitration Association (“Arbitration Rules”) and any applicable FERC regulations; provided, however, in the event of a conflict between the Arbitration Rules and the terms of this Section 10.1, the terms of this Section 10.1 shall prevail. 10.1.3 Arbitration . Unless otherwise agreed to by the Parties, the arbitrator shall render a decision within ninety (90) days after appointment and shall notify the Parties in writing of such decision and the reasons therefor. The arbitrator shall be authorized only to interpret and apply the provisions of this Agreement and shall have no power to modify or change any provision of this Agreement in any manner. The decision of the arbitrator shall be final and binding upon the Parties, and judgment on the award may be entered in any court having jurisdiction. The decision of the arbitrator may be appealed solely on the grounds that the conduct of the arbitrator, or the decision itself, violated the standards set forth in the Federal Arbitration Act or the Administrative Dispute Resolution Act. The final decision of the arbitrator must also be filed with FERC if it affects jurisdictional rates, terms and conditions of service the Interconnection Customer’s Interconnection Facilities. 10.1.4 Costs . Each Party shall be responsible for its own costs incurred during the arbitration process and each Project Company shall be responsible in accordance with the Sharing Ratio of the cost of the arbitrator chosen, if applicable. 10.1.5 Federal Power Act . Except as provided in Section 10.17, nothing in this Agreement or the LGIA Co-Tenancy Agreement shall abrogate or otherwise limit a Party’s right to exercise any rights it may have under the Federal Power Act; provided, however, that, except in an Emergency, a Party shall not exercise its rights under the Federal Power Act until thirty (30) days after receipt of the applicable Notice of Dispute; provided, further, however, that, in the event that a dispute or claim or a material issue related to a dispute or claim subject to this Section 10.1 or Section 2.16 of the LGIA Co-Tenancy Agreement is the subject of a proceeding under the Federal Power Act, any Party may elect to stay any consideration thereof until such proceeding is concluded. 10.2 Assignment Restrictions. 10.2.1 Assignment . Except as provided in Section 10.2.2 or 10.2.4, no Party shall assign its rights or obligations under this Agreement and no Co-Tenant shall assign its Co-Tenancy Interests; provided, however, that such Party shall assign (such assignment not requiring consent of a Party) all of its rights under this Agreement and all of its Co-Tenancy Interests to a transferee of all of such Party’s rights in its Generating Facility (in which case such transferee shall be assigned and assume the transferring Party’s entire interest in both this Agreement and Co-Tenancy Interests (if any), pursuant to an agreement reasonably satisfactory to the other Party). 10.2.2 Financing; Right to Encumber . Notwithstanding anything in this Section 10.2 to the contrary and in addition to the rights and obligations of any Party set forth in any consent to assignment but subject to Section 4.10, each Project Company shall have the right to assign to its Lenders any of its rights and obligations under this Agreement and any of its Co-Tenancy Interests (if any), in each case, without consent, only for collateral security purposes to aid in providing financing for such Project Company’s Generating Facility and Co-Tenancy Interest (if any) in the Shared Facilities and Rights. At the requesting Project Company’s cost, the other Project Companies and the Manager each agrees to execute and deliver to and in favor of the Lenders a consent to assignment and such other documents customary for project finance transactions and reasonably requested by such Lenders and reasonably acceptable to the Parties. 10.2.3 Void . Any assignment in contravention of this Section 10.2 shall be null and void. 10.2.4 Subcontracts . Notwithstanding anything in this Section 10.2 to the contrary, a Party may enter into subcontracts to perform its obligations under this Agreement, but such Party shall not be relieved of any obligation hereunder. 10.3 Notices . Any notice, demand, or communication required or permitted to be given by any provision of this Agreement shall be deemed to have been sufficiently given or served for all purposes if delivered personally or by telecopy to the Party or, if sent by registered or certified mail, postage and charges prepaid, addressed to the Party’s address, as appropriate, which is set forth below or to such other address as a Party shall advise the other Parties from time to time in writing. The following shall survive expiration of the Term: (a) all obligations under this Agreement owed to a Party arising prior to or resulting from the expiration of, or on account of the breach of, this Agreement; (b) Sections 4.3.3 and 7.1, which shall survive to the full extent of the statute of limitations period applicable to any Claim, (c) the resolution of any dispute or claim submitted pursuant to this Agreement prior to, or resulting from, the expiration of the Term; and (d) Articles 1, 9 and 10 (other than Sections 10.16(a) and 10.18) and Sections 6.1.3, 7.2 and 7.3. 10.5 Waivers . No (a) failure or delay on the part of a Party in exercising any of its rights under this Agreement or in insisting upon strict performance of provisions of this Agreement, (b) partial exercise by a Party of any of its rights under this Agreement or (c) course of dealing among the Parties shall constitute a waiver of the rights of any Party under this Agreement. Any waiver of rights shall be effective only by a written instrument signed by the Party granting any such waiver, and such instrument shall not operate as a waiver of, or estoppel with respect to, any subsequent failure to comply herewith. 10.6 No Partnership . This Agreement shall not be interpreted or construed to create an association, joint venture, agency relationship or partnership between the Parties or to impose any partnership obligation or partnership liability upon any Party. Except as otherwise agreed to by the Parties or expressly provided herein, no Party shall have any right, power or authority to enter into any agreement or undertaking for, or act on behalf of, or to act as or be an agent or representative of, or to otherwise bind, the other Party. THE PARTIES SHALL NOT BE CONSIDERED FIDUCIARIES IN CONNECTION WITH THIS AGREEMENT OR THE LGIA CO-TENANCY AGREEMENT, BUT RATHER SHALL BE FREE TO ACT ON AN ARM’S-LENGTH BASIS IN ACCORDANCE WITH THEIR OWN RESPECTIVE SELF-INTERESTS, SUBJECT, HOWEVER, TO THE OBLIGATIONS OF THE PARTIES TO ACT IN GOOD FAITH IN THEIR DEALINGS WITH EACH OTHER WITH RESPECT TO ACTIVITIES HEREUNDER AND THE LGIA CO-TENANCY AGREEMENT. No Project Company nor any Affiliate of a Project Company shall be precluded from engaging in any activities, including activities similar or identical to those to be conducted by the other Project Companies, in respect of its Generating Facility, the Shared Facilities and Rights or the LGIA or any activities incidental or related thereto, in each case, except as provided in this Agreement or as agreed to by the Project Companies. 10.7 Headings . The captions of the Articles and Sections of this Agreement are solely for convenience and shall not be deemed a part of this Agreement for the purpose of construing the meaning of this Agreement or for any other purpose. 10.8 Governing Law . This Agreement and the rights of the Parties hereunder shall be construed in accordance with the laws of the State of California to the extent not governed by the Federal Power Act, and all rights and remedies shall be governed by such laws without regard to principles of conflict of laws that require the application of another jurisdiction’s laws. Notwithstanding the foregoing sentence but except as provided in Section 10.17, nothing in this Agreement shall be construed as limiting the Parties’ rights and remedies under the Federal Power Act. 10.9 Severability . The invalidity or enforceability of any particular provision of this Agreement shall not affect the other provisions hereof, and this Agreement shall be construed in all respects as if such invalid or unenforceable provisions were omitted, and in lieu of such invalid or unenforceable provision, there shall be added automatically as a part of this Agreement a valid and enforceable provision as similar in terms to such invalid or unenforceable provision as may be possible. 10.10 Entire Agreement . This Agreement is the entire agreement and understanding among the Parties in respect of the subject matter hereof and supersedes all prior negotiations, understandings and writings among the Parties with respect to the subject matter hereof. This Agreement shall not be construed in any manner to amend or otherwise modify the LGIA or the LGIA Co-Tenancy Agreement or any other Shared Facilities and Rights Agreement. 10.11 Counterparts . This Agreement may be executed in any number of counterparts with the same effect as if all the Parties had signed the same document. All counterparts shall be construed together and shall constitute one instrument. 10.12 Successors and Assigns . This Agreement shall be binding upon and inure to the benefit of all the Parties and their respective successors and permitted assigns. 10.13 Third-Party Beneficiaries . This Agreement is intended solely for the benefit of the Parties, and the Parties expressly disclaim any intent to create any rights in any third party as a third-party beneficiary to this Agreement. 10.14 Joint Preparation . This Agreement shall be considered for all purposes as having been prepared through the joint efforts of the Parties and shall not be construed against any Party as a result of the preparation, substitution, submission or other event of the negotiation, drafting or execution of this Agreement. 10.15 Amendment . This Agreement may be amended, supplemented or modified only by a written instrument duly executed by or on behalf of each Party. 10.16 Running with the Land; Survival of Rights; Memorandum. (a) The Shared Facilities and Rights and the Shared Premises shall be held, conveyed, assigned, hypothecated, encumbered, used and occupied, subject to the covenants, terms and provisions set forth in this Agreement, which covenants, terms and provisions shall run with the land, and shall be binding upon and inure to the benefit of each Party and each other Person having any interest therein during such Party’s ownership of the Shared Facilities and Rights and the Shared Premises, and their respective grantees, heirs, successors and permitted assigns, and shall create privity of contract and estate among the Parties and their respective grantees, heirs, successors and permitted assigns. (b) The provisions of this Agreement will control with regard to any provisions of this Agreement that may be in conflict with the Memorandum of Agreement recorded in the official real estate records of the counties in which the Shared Premises are located. 10.17 Mobile Sierra . The Parties agree that all rates, terms and conditions as specified in this Agreement shall remain in effect in accordance with their terms and shall not be subject to change through application to FERC pursuant to the provisions of Section 205 or Section 206 of the Federal Power Act of 1935, as amended, 16 U.S.C. §§ 792 et seq. Absent agreement of the Parties to a proposed change, the standard of review for changes to any section of this Agreement by a Party, a non-Party or FERC acting sue sponte, shall be the “public interest” standard of review set forth in United Gas Pipe Line Co. v. Mobile Gas Service Corp., 350 U.S. 332 (1956) and Federal Power Commission v. Sierra Pacific Power Co., 350 U.S. 348 (1956), or will be the most stringent standard permissible under then-Applicable Law. 10.18 Confidentiality . Each Party agrees to maintain the confidentiality of information clearly identified at the time of delivery as confidential provided by a Party pursuant to this Agreement or the LGIA Co-Tenancy Agreement, except that such information may be disclosed (a) to Affiliates, managers, members, directors, officers, employees, advisors, agents, consultants, lenders and potential lenders, investors and purchasers to or of a Party or any of its Affiliates (and their respective advisors, consultants and counsel); it being understood that the Persons to whom such disclosure is made will be informed of the confidential nature of such information, (b) to the extent required by any Governmental Authority having jurisdiction over the receiving Party or Applicable Law, (c) in any legal action or proceeding relating to this Agreement, the LGIA Co-Tenancy Agreement or either Generating Facility, or (d) to the extent such information (i) becomes publicly available other than by breach of this Section 10.18, (ii) was available to the receiving Party on a non-confidential basis prior to its disclosure by the disclosing Party, (iii) becomes available to the receiving Party on a non-confidential basis from a third-Person not under any obligation to the disclosing Party not to disclose such information or (iv) is independently developed by the receiving Party. 10.19 Further Assurances . Each Party shall take all such further actions, and execute and deliver all such further instruments or documents, as may be reasonably requested by any other Party to effectuate the purposes of this Agreement. 10.20 Future Generating Facility . The Parties acknowledge that a new battery storage facility may be developed in the future by an Affiliate of each of Desert 250, Desert 300, Sunlight Storage and Sunlight Storage II. Upon the reasonable request of the owner of such new generating facility, the Parties agree to cooperate in good faith to amend and restate this Agreement to add such owner as a Party hereunder with usage rights (but no Co-Tenancy Interest) and obligations substantially similar to those of Sunlight Storage and Sunlight Storage II hereunder. 10.21 Master Agreement Event of Default . 10.21.1 Exercise of Remedies . Each of Sunlight Storage and Sunlight Storage II acknowledges the right of the Secured Parties, upon the occurrence and during the continuation of an Event of Default (as defined in the Master Agreements) and delivery by the Master Administrative Agent of written notice of such Event of Default to Sunlight Storage and Sunlight Storage II, to exercise and enforce all rights of the Co-Tenants under this Agreement. Upon the occurrence and during the continuation of an Event of Default (as defined in the Master Agreements) and the exercise by the Secured Parties of any of their remedies under the Master Agreements, the Secured Parties or any agent or designee thereof may assign their or its rights and interests and the rights and interests of the Co-Tenants under this Agreement to any person that (i) is a purchaser or transferee of any Desert Generating Facility and (ii) assumes the obligations of a Co-Tenant under this Agreement arising from and after the date of such assignment. Each of Sunlight Storage and Sunlight Storage II acknowledges and agrees, notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained in this Agreement, that none of the following events shall constitute a default by any Co-Tenant under this Agreement or require the consent of Sunlight Storage or Sunlight Storage II: (i) the operation of any Desert Generating Facility by or on behalf of the Secured Parties following the occurrence and continuation of an Event of Default under the Master Agreements and the related documents, or (ii) foreclosure or any other enforcement of the Master Agreements (or any other related security or pledge document) by the Secured Parties. 10.21.2 Sunlight Storage Rights . Sunlight Storage acknowledges that, notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, upon the occurrence and continuation of an Event of Default (as defined in the Master Agreements), Sunlight Storage may not exercise any consent or approval right granted to it pursuant to this Agreement that could reasonably be expected to materially adversely affect the Secured Parties’ exercise of their rights and remedies pursuant to the Master Agreements and Financing Documents (as defined in the Master Agreements); provided that in no event shall the foregoing be deemed to apply to the following provisions: a) Section 2.1 with respect to Sunlight Storage’s rights to consent to a wind-up or termination of the Shared Facilities and Rights or this Agreement; b) Section 4.3.2(c), with respect to any termination of any Shared Facilities and Rights Agreements; c) Section 4.3.2(c), with respect to any execution, material amendment to, issuance of a material change order under, or waiver of a material provision of any Shared Facilities and Rights Agreement, to the extent any such execution, amendment, issuance of a change order, or waiver could reasonably be expected to have an adverse effect with respect to Sunlight Storage or the Sunlight Storage Generating Facility; d) Section 4.3.2(f), with respect to any dispositions of any Shared Facilities and Rights; provided, that the consent of Sunlight Storage shall not be required with respect to a disposition of the entirety of the Shared Facilities and Rights, so long as following such disposition Sunlight Storage shall continue to have rights to use and access the Shared Facilities under this Agreement on the terms and conditions consistent with its rights to use and access such Shared Facilities prior to such disposition; e) Section 4.3.2(h); and f) Section 10.15, with respect to material amendments that could reasonably be expected to have an adverse effect with respect to Sunlight Storage or the Sunlight Storage Generating Facility. 10.21.3 Sunlight Storage II Rights . Sunlight Storage II acknowledges that, notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, upon the occurrence and continuation of an Event of Default (as defined in the Master Agreements), Sunlight Storage II may not exercise any consent or approval right granted to it pursuant to this Agreement that could reasonably be expected to materially adversely affect the Secured Parties’ exercise of their rights and remedies pursuant to the Master Agreements and Financing Documents (as defined in the Master Agreements); provided that in no event shall the foregoing be deemed to apply to the following provisions: a) Section 2.1 with respect to Sunlight Storage II’s rights to consent to a wind-up or termination of the Shared Facilities and Rights or this Agreement; b) Section 4.3.2(c), with respect to any termination of any Shared Facilities and Rights Agreements; c) Section 4.3.2(c), with respect to any execution, material amendment to, issuance of a material change order under, or waiver of a material provision of any Shared Facilities and Rights Agreement, to the extent any such execution, amendment, issuance of a change order, or waiver could reasonably be expected to have an adverse effect with respect to Sunlight Storage II or the Sunlight Storage II Generating Facility; d) Section 4.3.2(f), with respect to any dispositions of any Shared Facilities and Rights; provided, that the consent of Sunlight Storage II shall not be required with respect to a disposition of the entirety of the Shared Facilities and Rights, so long as following such disposition Sunlight Storage II shall continue to have rights to use and access the Shared Facilities under this Agreement on the terms and conditions consistent with its rights to use and access such Shared Facilities prior to such disposition; e) Section 4.3.2(h); and f) Section 10.15, with respect to material amendments that could reasonably be expected to have an adverse effect with respect to Sunlight Storage II or the Sunlight Storage II Generating Facility. 10.22 Shortfall Event . 10.22.1 Shortfall Event Payment . (a) Sunlight Storage Shortfall Event Payment . Sunlight Storage acknowledges and agrees that, upon a Shortfall Event, Sunlight Storage shall confer in good faith with the Master Administrative Agent (acting pursuant to the directions of the Secured Parties pursuant to the Intercreditor Agreements (as defined in the Master Agreements)) to determine the amount of the Shortfall, if any, attributable solely to the Shared Rights held by Sunlight Storage (the “Sunlight Storage Shortfall Amount”). In the event that Sunlight Storage and the Master Administrative Agent do not come to an agreement regarding the Sunlight Storage Shortfall Amount within 30 days after the initiation of such discussions, then the parties shall jointly engage an independent arbitrator in accordance with Section 10.1 to determine the Sunlight Storage Shortfall Amount, and the determination of such independent arbitrator shall be binding; provided that, in no event shall the Sunlight Storage Shortfall Amount exceed $15,000,000. The Sunlight Storage Shortfall Amount owed by Sunlight Storage, if any, shall be payable within 30 days of the determination of such amount. The Parties acknowledge and agree that the Guarantor shall guarantee payment of the Sunlight Storage Shortfall Amount, if any, pursuant to the Sunlight Storage Shortfall Guaranty. (b) Sunlight Storage II Shortfall Event Payment . Sunlight Storage II acknowledges and agrees that, upon a Shortfall Event, Sunlight Storage II shall confer in good faith with the Master Administrative Agent (acting pursuant to the directions of the Secured Parties pursuant to the Intercreditor Agreements (as defined in the Master Agreements)) to determine the amount of the Shortfall, if any, attributable solely to the Shared Rights held by Sunlight Storage II (the “Sunlight Storage II Shortfall Amount”). In the event that Sunlight Storage II and the Master Administrative Agent do not come to an agreement regarding the Sunlight Storage II Shortfall Amount within 30 days after the initiation of such discussions, then the parties shall jointly engage an independent arbitrator in accordance with Section 10.1 to determine the Sunlight Storage II Shortfall Amount, and the determination of such independent arbitrator shall be binding; provided that, in no event shall the Sunlight Storage II Shortfall Amount exceed $15,000,000. The Sunlight Storage II Shortfall Amount owed by Sunlight Storage II, if any, shall be payable within 30 days of the determination of such amount. The Parties acknowledge and agree that the Guarantor shall guarantee payment of the Sunlight Storage II Shortfall Amount, if any, pursuant to the Sunlight Storage II Shortfall Guaranty. 10.22.2 Downgrade Event . (a) Sunlight Storage Downgrade Event . Sunlight Storage acknowledges and agrees that, in the event that a Downgrade Event occurs, Sunlight Storage shall as promptly as reasonably practicable notify the Master Administrative Agent in writing of such Downgrade Event in accordance with the notice information and procedures set forth in the Sunlight Storage Shortfall Guaranty. No later than 30 days after such Downgrade Event, Sunlight Storage shall deliver to the Master Administrative Agent a letter of credit issued by an Acceptable Issuer in the amount of not less than $15,000,000 under which the Master Administrative Agent is the beneficiary (the “Replacement LC”). The Replacement LC shall have an expiration date of not less than one year after the date of issuance and shall provide that the Master Administrative Agent is permitted to draw on the full amount of the Replacement LC if the Replacement LC will expire within 30 days and has not been renewed or replaced, which proceeds of such draw shall be held as cash collateral by the Master Administrative Agent in respect of Sunlight Storage’s obligations under Section 10.22.1. Any such cash collateral or Replacement LC shall be returned to Sunlight Storage upon the earliest of (i) the termination of this Agreement, (ii) payment in full of any Sunlight Storage Shortfall Amount owing under Section 10.22.1, (iii) the delivery to the Master Administrative Agent of a new Replacement LC (if the Master Administrative Agent is holding cash collateral) and (iv) payment in full of all outstanding obligations of Desert 250 and Desert 300 under the Master Agreements and other “Financing Documents” (as defined in the Master Agreements). Upon delivery of the Replacement LC to the Master Administrative Agent, the Sunlight Storage Shortfall Guaranty shall terminate in accordance with the terms thereof, and Sunlight Storage shall have no further obligation to maintain the Sunlight Storage Shortfall Guaranty. (b) Sunlight Storage II Downgrade Event . Sunlight Storage II acknowledges and agrees that, in the event that a Downgrade Event occurs, Sunlight Storage II shall as promptly as reasonably practicable notify the Master Administrative Agent in writing of such Downgrade Event in accordance with the notice information and procedures set forth in the Sunlight Storage II Shortfall Guaranty. No later than 30 days after such Downgrade Event, Sunlight Storage II shall deliver to the Master Administrative Agent a letter of credit issued by an Acceptable Issuer in the amount of not less than $15,000,000 under which the Master Administrative Agent is the beneficiary (the “Replacement LC”). The Replacement LC shall have an expiration date of not less than one year after the date of issuance and shall provide that the Master Administrative Agent is permitted to draw on the full amount of the Replacement LC if the Replacement LC will expire within 30 days and has not been renewed or replaced, which proceeds of such draw shall be held as cash collateral by the Master Administrative Agent in respect of Sunlight Storage’s obligations under Section 10.22.1. Any such cash collateral or Replacement LC shall be returned to Sunlight Storage II upon the earliest of (i) the termination of this Agreement, (ii) payment in full of any Sunlight Storage II Shortfall Amount owing under Section 10.22.1, (iii) the delivery to the Master Administrative Agent of a new Replacement LC (if the Master Administrative Agent is holding cash collateral) and (iv) payment in full of all outstanding obligations of Desert 250 and Desert 300 under the Master Agreements and other “Financing Documents” (as defined in the Master Agreements). Upon delivery of the Replacement LC to the Master Administrative Agent, the Sunlight Storage II Shortfall Guaranty shall terminate in accordance with the terms thereof, and Sunlight Storage II shall have no further obligation to maintain the Sunlight Storage II Shortfall Guaranty.
